<font color="#FF0000">FLICKERING FLAME</font><br>
<tt>Sat Aug  9 11:14:43 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Doc Spatz:<br><br>
I prefer to talk WITH you rather than TO you.<br>
My feelings are not a template for every person who served in Viet Nam. I speak only for myself... except I have been influenced by those who served in Viet Nam with me.  &quot;Ergo cogito sum,&quot; reminds me that I am the sum of my thoughts.  My fallen and injured brothers are very much in my thoughts.<br><br>
In my ancient language there were no words for assume, admit, sorry, because, expect, we, us, them, weed, pest, forgive, forget, believe, could, should, doubt and a host of other words that did not exist.<br><br>
I grew up in a &quot;Norman Rockwell&quot; America, small rural town. To me, the word &quot;cool&quot; meant something like window fan or an iced down watermellon.  As a small boy, I called black people Negros or Colored people, out of respect... I called them &quot;niggers&quot; when I became a &quot;we&quot; thinker... a subscriber to others values.  Fortunately, I escaped that group.<br>
I advocated that &quot;Fords&quot; were far superior to &quot;Chevrolets&quot; without the benefit of any comparative research... I just went along with the larger &quot;we&quot; group.  When my Dad bought a new Chevy I had to change camps, something I did not enjoy doing.<br>
Ultimately, I became an independent thinker if that is an accurate statement!  I was influenced by my Mother and Father and my extended family, Roy Rogers, Batman, our Pastor, the Boy Scouts of America, Mr. Proctor who sold me shotgun shells on credit, Pop Corn (an old black man who invited me to tag along on squirrel hunts), many school teachers... the list is endless.  Am I independent or am I a by-product of others?<br>
Somewhere, I learned to be patriotic, say Mamam and Sir to elders, salute the Flag, carry groceries for my Mother, stand when ladies entered the room... and immitate my Father, Uncles, Cousins, and especially my Grandfathers when called to war.  These were some of my internalized values.<br>
Many taught me that it was wrong to kill, lie or be lied to, steal, curse, cry, and show cowardice.  My tongue could swell and fill my dry mouth, I could urinate in my pants, feel my hands and feet swell with hives, lose my voice, experience horror... but I was not allowed to be afraid.<br>
It is difficult for me to accept those who do not share my strongest beliefs.  I have trouble confirming when I wish to condemn.  I have not been able to forgive and forget.<br>
What you and I say here is subject to agreement and disagreement, praise and ridicule
<p><code>-- eramon@edumaster.net  (Edward Ramon) </code><p>


